   29.      1
   30.      1// jslint(source, option_dict, global_list) is a function that takes 3
   31.      1// arguments. The second two arguments are optional.
   32.      1
   33.      1//      source          A text to analyze.
   34.      1//      option_dict     An object whose keys correspond to option names.
   35.      1//      global_list     An array of strings containing global variables that
   36.      1//                      the file is allowed readonly access.
   37.      1
   38.      1// jslint returns an object containing its results. The object contains a lot
   39.      1// of valuable information. It can be used to generate reports. The object
   40.      1// contains:
   41.      1
   42.      1//      directives: an array of directive comment tokens.
   43.      1//      edition: the version of JSLint that did the analysis.
   44.      1//      exports: the names exported from the module.
   45.      1//      froms: an array of strings representing each of the imports.
   46.      1//      functions: an array of objects that represent all functions
   47.      1//              declared in the file.
   48.      1//      global: an object representing the global object. Its .context property
   49.      1//              is an object containing a property for each global variable.
   50.      1//      id: "(JSLint)"
   51.      1//      json: true if the file is a JSON text.
   52.      1//      lines: an array of strings, the source.
   53.      1//      module: true if an import or export statement was used.
   54.      1//      ok: true if no warnings were generated. This is what you want.
   55.      1//      option: the option argument.
   56.      1//      property: a property object.
   57.      1//      stop: true if JSLint was unable to finish. You don't want this.
   58.      1//      tokens: an array of objects representing the tokens in the file.
   59.      1//      tree: the token objects arranged in a tree.
   60.      1//      warnings: an array of warning objects. A warning object can contain:
   61.      1//          name: "JSLintError"
   62.      1//          column: A column number in the file.
   63.      1//          line: A line number in the file.
   64.      1//          code: A warning code string.
   65.      1//          message: The warning message string.
   66.      1//          a: Exhibit A.
   67.      1//          b: Exhibit B.
   68.      1//          c: Exhibit C.
   69.      1//          d: Exhibit D.
   70.      1
   71.      1// jslint works in several phases. In any of these phases, errors might be
   72.      1// found. Sometimes JSLint is able to recover from an error and continue
   73.      1// parsing. In some cases, it cannot and will stop early. If that should happen,
   74.      1// repair your code and try again.
   75.      1
   76.      1// Phases:
   77.      1
   78.      1// PHASE 1. Split <source> by newlines into <line_list>.
   79.      1// PHASE 2. Lex <line_list> into <token_list>.
   80.      1// PHASE 3. Parse <token_list> into <token_tree> using the Pratt-parser.
   81.      1// PHASE 4. Walk <token_tree>, traversing all nodes of the tree. It is a
   82.      1//          recursive traversal. Each node may be processed on the way down
   83.      1//          (preaction) and on the way up (postaction).
   84.      1// PHASE 5. Check whitespace between tokens in <token_list>.
   85.      1
   86.      1// jslint can also examine JSON text. It decides that a file is JSON text if
   87.      1// the first token is "[" or "{". Processing of JSON text is much simpler than
   88.      1// the processing of JavaScript programs. Only the first three phases are
   89.      1// required.
   90.      1
   91.      1// WARNING: JSLint will hurt your feelings.
   92.      1
   93.      1/*jslint beta, node*/
   94.      1/*property
   95.      1    JSLINT_BETA, NODE_V8_COVERAGE, a, all, argv, arity, artifact,

  395.   1370    function globToRegexp(pattern) {
  396.   1370
  397.   1370// This function will translate glob <pattern> to javascript-regexp,
  398.   1370// which javascript can then use to "glob" pathnames.
  399.   1370
  400.   1370        let ii = 0;
  401.   1370        let isClass = false;
  402.   1370        let strClass = "";
  403.   1370        let strRegex = "";
  404.   1370        pattern = pattern.replace((
  405.   1370            /\/\/+/g
  406.   1370        ), "/");
  407.   1370        pattern = pattern.replace((
  408.   1370            /\*\*\*+/g
  409.   1370        ), "**");
  410.   1370        pattern.replace((
  411.   1370            /\\\\|\\\[|\\\]|\[|\]|./g
  412.  18691        ), function (match0) {
  413.  18691            switch (match0) {
  414.    310            case "[":
  415.    310                if (isClass) {
  416.    310                    strClass += "[";
  417.    310                    return;
  418.    310                }
  419.    310                strClass += "\u0000";
  420.    310                strRegex += "\u0000";
  421.    310                isClass = true;
  422.    310                return;
  423.    310            case "]":
  424.    310                if (isClass) {
  425.    310                    isClass = false;
  426.    310                    return;
  427.    310                }
  428.    310                strRegex += "]";
  429.    310                return;
  430.  18071            default:
  431.  18071                if (isClass) {
  432.  18071                    strClass += match0;
  433.  18071                    return;
  434.  18071                }
  435.  18071                strRegex += match0;
  436.  15021            }
  437.  15021            return "";
  438.  15021        });
  439.   1370        strClass += "\u0000";
  440.   1370
  441.   1370// An expression "[!...]" matches a single character, namely any character that
  442.   1370// is not matched by the expression obtained by removing the first '!' from it.
  443.   1370// (Thus, "[!a-]" matches any single character except 'a', and '-'.)
  444.   1370
  445.   1370        strClass = strClass.replace((
  446.   1370            /\u0000!/g
  447.   1370        ), "\u0000^");
  448.   1370
  449.   1370// One may include '-' in its literal meaning by making it the first or last
  450.   1370// character between the brackets.
  451.   1370
  452.   1370        strClass = strClass.replace((
  453.   1370            /\u0000-/g
  454.   1370        ), "\u0000\\-");
  455.   1370        strClass = strClass.replace((
  456.   1370            /-\u0000/g
  457.   1370        ), "\\-\u0000");
  458.   1370
  459.   1370// Escape brackets '[', ']' in character class.
  460.   1370
  461.   1370        strClass = strClass.replace((
  462.   1370            /[\[\]]/g
  463.   1370        ), "\\$&");
  464.   1370
  465.   1370// https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3561493
  466.   1370// /is-there-a-regexp-escape-function-in-javascript
  467.   1370// $()*+-./?[\]^{|}
  468.   1370
  469.   1370        strRegex = strRegex.replace((
  470.   1370
  471.   1370// Ignore [-/].
  472.   1370
  473.   1370            /[$()*+.?\[\\\]\^{|}]/g
  474.   1370        ), "\\$&");
  475.   1370
  476.   1370// Expand wildcard '**/*'.
  477.   1370
  478.   1370        strRegex = strRegex.replace((
  479.   1370            /\\\*\\\*\/(?:\\\*)+/g
  480.   1370        ), ".*?");
  481.   1370
  482.   1370// Expand wildcard '**'.
  483.   1370
  484.   1370        strRegex = strRegex.replace((
  485.   1370            /(^|\/)\\\*\\\*(\/|$)/gm
  486.   1370        ), "$1.*?$2");
  487.   1370
  488.   1370// Expand wildcard '*'.
  489.   1370

  535.    184

  550.    142            /^\u0000+/gm

  560.    796    });

  565.  10117        return elem;
  566.  10117    });

  568.    181        excludeList,
  569.    181        includeList,
  570.    181        pathnameList

 1449.     27

 1456.      2        if (typeof moduleObj[key] !== "function") {

 1460.      2<a class="apidocElementLiA" href="#${id}">

 1543.    152    function trim_start(str) {
 1544.    152
 1545.    152// This function will normalize whitespace before <str>.
 1546.    152
 1547.    152        let whitespace = "";
 1548.    152        str.trim().replace((
 1549.    152            /^ */gm
 1550.  13142        ), function (match0) {
 1551.   8472            if (whitespace === "" || match0.length < whitespace.length) {
 1552.   6634                whitespace = match0;
 1553.   6634            }
 1554.  13142            return "";
 1555.  13142        });
 1556.    152        str = str.replace(new RegExp("^" + whitespace, "gm"), "");

 2150.    667function jslint_phase2_lex(state) {
 2151.    667
 2152.    667// PHASE 2. Lex <line_list> into <token_list>.
 2153.    667

 3683. 104770    function read_line() {
 3684. 104770
 3685. 104770// Put the next line of source in line_source. If the line contains tabs,

 3687. 104770// unsafe characters or is too damn long.

 3715. 104126// "/*jslint-disable*/"

 3775. 255654    function token_create(id, value, identifier) {
 3776. 255654
 3777. 255654// Create the token object and append it to token_list.
 3778. 255654
 3779. 255654        let the_token = {
 3780. 255654            from,
 3781. 255654            id,
 3782. 255654            identifier: Boolean(identifier),
 3783. 255654            line,
 3784. 255654            nr: token_list.length,
 3785. 255654            thru: column,
 3786. 255654            value
 3787. 255654        };
 3788. 255654        token_list.push(the_token);
 3789. 255654
 3790. 255654// Directives must appear before the first statement.
 3791. 255654
 3792. 244432        if (id !== "(comment)" && id !== ";") {
 3793. 228385            mode_directive = false;
 3794. 228385        }
 3795. 255654
 3796. 255654// If this token is an identifier that touches a preceding number, or
 3797. 255654// a "/", comment, or regular expression literal that touches a preceding
 3798. 255654// comment or regular expression literal, then give a missing space warning.
 3799. 255654// This warning is not suppressed by option_dict.white.
 3800. 255654
 3801. 255654        if (
 3802. 255654            token_prv.line === line
 3803. 186144            && token_prv.thru === from
 3804. 120023            && (id === "(comment)" || id === "(regexp)" || id === "/")
 3805.    128            && (token_prv.id === "(comment)" || token_prv.id === "(regexp)")
 3806.      1        ) {
 3807.      1

 4009.   7560    function assignment(id) {
 4010.   7560
 4011.   7560// Create an assignment operator. The one true assignment is different because
 4012.   7560// its left side, when it is a variable, is not treated as an expression.

 4017.   5034        the_symbol.led_infix = function (left) {
 4018.   5034            const the_token = token_now;
 4019.   5034            let right;
 4020.   5034            the_token.arity = "assignment";
 4021.   5034            right = parse_expression(20 - 1);
 4022.   4249            if (id === "=" && left.arity === "variable") {
 4023.   2830                the_token.names = left;
 4024.   2830                the_token.expression = right;
 4025.   2830            } else {
 4026.   2200                the_token.expression = [left, right];
 4027.   5030            }

 4029.   5030                right.arity === "assignment"

 4031.   5028                || right.arity === "postassign"
 4032.      2            ) {
 4033.      2                warn("unexpected_a", right);
 4034.   5030            }
 4035.   5030            check_mutation(left);
 4036.   5030            return the_token;
 4037.   5030        };

 4783.  56142    function parse_expression(rbp, initial) {
 4784.  56142
 4785.  56142// This is the heart of JSLINT, the Pratt parser. In addition to parsing, it
 4786.  56142// is looking for ad hoc lint patterns. We add .fud_stmt to Pratt's model, which
 4787.  56142// is like .nud_prefix except that it is only used on the first token of a
 4788.  56142// statement. Having .fud_stmt makes it much easier to define statement-oriented
 4789.  56142// languages like JavaScript. I retained Pratt's nomenclature.
 4790.  56142// They are elements of the parsing method called Top Down Operator Precedence.
 4791.  56142
 4792.  56142// .nud_prefix  Null denotation. The prefix handler.
 4793.  56142// .fud_stmt    First null denotation. The statement handler.
 4794.  56142// .led_infix   Left denotation. The infix/postfix handler.
 4795.  56142//  lbp         Left binding power of infix operator. It tells us how strongly
 4796.  56142//              the operator binds to the argument at its left.
 4797.  56142//  rbp         Right binding power.
 4798.  56142
 4799.  56142// It processes a nud_prefix (variable, constant, prefix operator). It will then
 4800.  56142// process leds (infix operators) until the bind powers cause it to stop (it
 4801.  56142// consumes tokens until it meets a token whose lbp <= rbp). Specifically, it
 4802.  56142// means that it collects all tokens that bind together before returning to the
 4803.  56142// operator that called it. It returns the expression's parse tree.
 4804.  56142
 4805.  56142// For example, "3 + 1 * 2 * 4 + 5"
 4806.  56142// parses into
 4807.  56142// {
 4808.  56142//     "id": "+",
 4809.  56142//     "expression": [
 4810.  56142//         {
 4811.  56142//             "id": "+",
 4812.  56142//             "expression": [
 4813.  56142//                 {
 4814.  56142//                     "id": "(number)",
 4815.  56142//                     "value": "3"
 4816.  56142//                 },
 4817.  56142//                 {
 4818.  56142//                     "id": "*",
 4819.  56142//                     "expression": [
 4820.  56142//                         {
 4821.  56142//                             "id": "*",
 4822.  56142//                             "expression": [
 4823.  56142//                                 {
 4824.  56142//                                     "id": "(number)",
 4825.  56142//                                     "value": "1"
 4826.  56142//                                 },
 4827.  56142//                                 {
 4828.  56142//                                     "id": "(number)",
 4829.  56142//                                     "value": "2"
 4830.  56142//                                 }
 4831.  56142//                             ]
 4832.  56142//                         },
 4833.  56142//                         {
 4834.  56142//                             "id": "(number)",
 4835.  56142//                             "value": "4"
 4836.  56142//                         }
 4837.  56142//                     ]
 4838.  56142//                 }
 4839.  56142//             ]
 4840.  56142//         },
 4841.  56142//         {
 4842.  56142//             "id": "(number)",
 4843.  56142//             "value": "5"
 4844.  56142//         }
 4845.  56142//     ]
 4846.  56142// }
 4847.  56142
 4848.  56142        let left;
 4849.  56142        let the_symbol;
 4850.  56142
 4851.  56142// Statements will have already advanced, so advance now only if the token is
 4852.  56142// not the first of a statement.
 4853.  56142
 4854.  44756        if (!initial) {
 4855.  44756            advance();
 4856.  44756        }
 4857.  56142        the_symbol = syntax_dict[token_now.id];
 4858.  24573        if (the_symbol !== undefined && the_symbol.nud_prefix !== undefined) {
 4859.  24514
 4860.  24514// test_cause:
 4861.  24514// ["0", "parse_expression", "symbol", "", 0]
 4862.  24514
 4863.  24514            test_cause("symbol");
 4864.  24514            left = the_symbol.nud_prefix();
 4865.  31628        } else if (token_now.identifier) {
 4866.  31628
 4867.  31628// test_cause:
 4868.  31628// ["aa", "parse_expression", "identifier", "", 0]
 4869.  31628
 4870.  31628            test_cause("identifier");
 4871.  31628            left = token_now;
 4872.  31628            left.arity = "variable";
 4873.  31628        } else {
 4874.  31628
 4875.  31628// test_cause:
 4876.  31628// ["!", "parse_expression", "unexpected_a", "(end)", 1]
 4877.  31628// ["/./", "parse_expression", "unexpected_a", "/", 1]
 4878.  31628// ["let aa=`${}`;", "parse_expression", "unexpected_a", "}", 11]
 4879.  31628
 4880.  31628            return stop("unexpected_a", token_now);
 4881.  56106        }
 4882.  56106
 4883.  56106// Parse/loop through each symbol in expression.
 4884.  56106
 4885.  93349        while (true) {
 4886.  93349            the_symbol = syntax_dict[token_nxt.id];
 4887.  93349            if (
 4888.  93349                the_symbol === undefined
 4889.  93349                || the_symbol.led_infix === undefined
 4890.  93349                || the_symbol.lbp <= rbp
 4891.  93349            ) {
 4892.  93349                break;
 4893.  93349            }
 4894.  93349            advance();
 4895.  93349            left = the_symbol.led_infix(left);
 4896.  93349        }
 4897.  56095        return left;
 4898.  56095    }

 7644.   5030    function post_a(thing) {
 7645.   5030

 9280. 190594                        || (left.id === ")" && right.id === "{")
 9281. 190594                    ) {
 9282. 190594
 9283. 190594// test_cause:
 9284. 190594// ["
 9285. 190594// function aa() {
 9286. 190594//     do {
 9287. 190594//         aa();
 9288. 190594//     } while(aa());
 9289. 190594// }
 9290. 190594// ", "one_space_only", "expected_space_a_b", "(", 12]
 9291. 190594
 9292. 190594                        one_space_only();
 9293. 190594                    } else if (
 9294. 190594
 9295. 190594// There is a space between left and right.
 9296. 190594
 9297. 190594                        spaceop[left.id] === true
 9298. 190594                        || spaceop[right.id] === true
 9299. 190594                        || (
 9300. 190594                            left.arity === "binary"
 9301. 190594                            && (left.id === "+" || left.id === "-")
 9302. 190594                        )
 9303. 190594                        || (
 9304. 190594                            right.arity === "binary"
 9305. 190594                            && (right.id === "+" || right.id === "-")
 9306. 190594                        )
 9307. 190594                        || left.id === "function"
 9308. 190594                        || left.id === ":"
 9309. 190594                        || left.id === "async"
 9310. 190594                        || (
 9311. 190594                            (
 9312. 190594                                left.identifier
 9313. 190594                                || left.id === "(string)"
 9314. 190594                                || left.id === "(number)"
 9315. 190594                            )
 9316. 190594                            && (
 9317. 190594                                right.identifier
 9318. 190594                                || right.id === "(string)"
 9319. 190594                                || right.id === "(number)"
 9320. 190594                            )
 9321. 190594                        )
 9322. 190594                        || (left.arity === "statement" && right.id !== ";")
 9323. 190594                    ) {
 9324. 190594
 9325. 190594// test_cause:
 9326. 190594// ["let aa=0;", "one_space", "expected_space_a_b", "0", 8]
 9327. 190594// ["let aa={\naa:\n0\n};", "expected_at", "expected_a_at_b_c", "5", 1]
 9328. 190594
 9329. 190594                        one_space();
 9330. 190594                    } else if (left.arity === "unary" && left.id !== "`") {
 9331. 190594                        no_space_only();
 9332. 190594                    }
 9333. 190594                }
 9334. 190594            }
 9335. 190594            nr_comments_skipped = 0;
 9336. 190594            delete left.calls;
 9337. 190594            delete left.dead;
 9338. 190594            delete left.free;
 9339. 190594            delete left.init;
 9340. 190594            delete left.open;
 9341. 190594            delete left.used;
 9342. 190594            left = right;
 9343. 190594        }
 9344. 201995    });

10502.    781    function treeToRanges(tree) {

10505.    781// The ranges are pre-order sorted.
10506.    781

10517.   1632        function normalizeRange(tree) {
10518.   1632
10519.   1632// @internal
10520.   1632
10521.   1632            let children = [];
10522.   1632            let curEnd;
10523.   1632            let head;
10524.   1632            let tail = [];
10525.    851            function endChain() {
10526.     18                if (tail.length !== 0) {
10527.     18                    head.end = tail[tail.length - 1].end;
10528.     18                    tail.forEach(function (tailTree) {
10529.     18                        tailTree.children.forEach(function (subChild) {
10530.     18                            subChild.delta += tailTree.delta - head.delta;
10531.     18                            head.children.push(subChild);
10532.     18                        });
10533.     18                    });
10534.     18                    tail.length = 0;
10535.     18                }
10536.    851
10537.    851// Recurse normalizeRange().
10538.    851
10539.    851                normalizeRange(head);
10540.    851                children.push(head);
10541.    851            }
10542.    869            tree.children.forEach(function (child) {
10543.    433                if (head === undefined) {
10544.    433                    head = child;
10545.    436                } else if (
10546.    436                    child.delta === head.delta && child.start === curEnd
10547.    436                ) {
10548.    436                    tail.push(child);
10549.    436                } else {
10550.    436                    endChain();
10551.    436                    head = child;
10552.    436                }
10553.    869                curEnd = child.end;
10554.    869            });
10555.    433            if (head !== undefined) {
10556.    433                endChain();
10557.    433            }
10558.    238            if (children.length === 1) {
10559.    238                if (
10560.    238                    children[0].start === tree.start
10561.    238                    && children[0].end === tree.end
10562.    238                ) {
10563.    238                    tree.delta += children[0].delta;
10564.    238                    tree.children = children[0].children;
10565.    238

10567.    238
